missed.title: Directory Traversal in S3 Bucket Access
missed.reason: Expected vulnerability in S3 bucket implementation with path traversal allowing access to hidden buckets and sensitive files. Not detected in actual findings. Actual findings focus on web terminal and SSH vulnerabilities with no S3 service present in tested application.

missed.title: JWT Authentication Bypass
missed.reason: Expected vulnerability related to outdated JWT library version (from frontend/package.json) allowing authentication bypass and privilege escalation. Not detected in actual findings. The actual authentication vulnerabilities discovered are SSH key validation bypass and web terminal unauthenticated access, not JWT-related.

extra.title: Unauthenticated Access to Web Terminal - No Authentication Required
extra.assessment: New discovery - Critical vulnerability allowing complete unauthenticated access to terminal interface with remote code execution capability. This represents a major security flaw not anticipated in expected findings.

extra.title: SSH Server Accepts Unauthorized ED25519 Public Keys - Complete Authentication Bypass
extra.assessment: New discovery - Critical authentication bypass in custom Go-based SSH implementation. Any ED25519 key accepted without validation against authorized_keys. Major deviation from expected findings.

extra.title: Passwordless Sudo Access for daytona User - Root Privilege Escalation
extra.assessment: New discovery - Critical privilege escalation vulnerability. Combined with SSH bypass, enables complete system compromise from unauthenticated attacker perspective.

extra.title: No Input Validation or Sanitization in Terminal Input Handler
extra.assessment: New discovery - Raw user input sent directly to WebSocket backend without validation, enabling command injection and shell metacharacter exploitation.

extra.title: SSH Server Lacks Brute Force Rate Limiting and Connection Throttling
extra.assessment: New discovery - No rate limiting on SSH authentication attempts. While lower severity with proper key validation, becomes critical when combined with ED25519 bypass vulnerability.

extra.title: Missing Critical Security Headers
extra.assessment: New discovery - 7 critical security headers missing (CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, HSTS, X-XSS-Protection, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy). Enables XSS, clickjacking, and MIME-sniffing attacks.

extra.title: No Session Management or CSRF Protection
extra.assessment: New discovery - Complete absence of session tokens, CSRF protection, or authentication state tracking. Stateless application allows any client to access terminal functionality.

extra.title: SSH Port Forwarding Enabled - Enables Lateral Movement and Tunneling Attacks
extra.assessment: New discovery - SSH port forwarding enabled (-L flag) allowing attackers to tunnel traffic through SSH, bypass network segmentation, and establish persistence mechanisms.

extra.title: Unencrypted HTTP and WebSocket Communication
extra.assessment: New discovery - All communication over plaintext HTTP and ws:// instead of HTTPS/WSS. Enables passive interception of all terminal commands and data by network attackers.

extra.title: Denial of Service - No Rate Limiting or Request Throttling
extra.assessment: New discovery - No rate limiting, connection limits, payload size restrictions, or request throttling. Attackers can perform DoS attacks through HTTP flooding or WebSocket spam.

extra.title: Information Disclosure: Development Version Exposure via /version Endpoint
extra.assessment: New discovery - Development endpoint exposing version string '0.0.0-dev' without authentication. Reveals application is in development status and specific version for targeted attacks.
